Very, very few things in life live up to their hype. A few that come to mind: 1. Good things come in small packages. 2. Blondes have more fun (save it). 3. Gary Danko is all that. Yes. Gary Danko is all that. It lives up to its rep. Yes, it's worth it. Yes, you will love it. If you don't like it, you're either in a bad mood or your pants are too tight. If your pants are too tight when you leave, you did it right. Everything you order will be perfect. The service will be stellar. There is no real reason to go into individual dishes or rave about specific wines. It's all good. In the true meaning of the phrase. All of it is good. More than good. Epically great. You cannot go wrong. Swirl the menu like a globe and let your finger land wherever. Order it. It will be amazing. Gary Danko you are the stuff of legend. Yet you're true. That's the best. You, the Northern Lights, the green flash and the softness of a baby's bottom. Believe the hype.

Seared Filet of Beef with Cumin Potatoes, Swiss Chard, Tomato-Corn Relish and Basil Butter Thinking I was in the USA and therefore beef should be eaten, these days, I know I prefer other meat better. I don't know that another review of Gary Danko is necessary but because I had such an amazing experience here I thought I'd share it (oh, and so I can add it to one of my Yelp lists). So I went with my friend Chai since we had won a gift certificate there from Zenfolio - thanks Zenfolio! We arrived just a little before our reservation so we sat at the bar and I ordered a Margaux (Cabernet Sauvignon-blend) Clos Margalaine, Bordeaux, France 1999 which is an amazing wine! It was one of the best Cabs I've had (although I am by no means a wine connoisseur). After we sat down and reviewed the menu we made our selections and got the five course dinner. From the app list I selected the Crispy Farm Egg with White Polenta, Royal Trumpet Mushrooms, Frisee and Pancetta. It is a relatively new item and is amazing! Great start to the meal and I love eggs especially when they are so fresh and runny too. Chai got the Seared Ahi Tuna with Avocado, Nori, Enoki Mushrooms and Lemon Soy Dressing. It sounded very Japanese since I've had all those ingredients in Japanese cuisine before. I tried it and it was tasty and flavorful and even the nori was really good (and I love nori!) Of course we had to try the Foie Gras (Seared Sonoma Foie Gras with Caramelized Red Onions and Vanilla Poached Rhubard). It was my first time trying foie gras which I had some reservations about, but hey I had to try it and it was so rich! We shared one order but it was still a perfect amount because of how rich the flavors were! For the fish and seafood course we both opted for the Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Puree, Black Trumpet Mushrooms, Edamame and Tarragon. Man this review has gone too long, suffice it to say that the meal was amazing and I'm looking forward to a return visit with maybe my sister who would no doubt enjoy it :)

I know you are thinking this is just another rave review for Gary Danko. And, it is, but it is also so much more - it is a rave review from a pesco-VEGETARIAN. Thats right, Gary does vegetarian, and he does it oh so very well. It might have helped that my fiance made a point of telling them that the birthday girl is a veghead when making the reservation, but there was no shortage of yummy sounding choices AND not the slightest hint of derision or annoyance at my meat free eating habits. We walked in for an early seating and were led to a beautiful corner table. I do admit that as the place filled up, we did feel a bit like we were dining with the couple next to us. But, they were very cool so that wasnt so bad. The server brought out this wonderful hook to put on the end of the table for my purse. For some reason, I was completely mesmerized by how cool the purse hook was. Yup, my inner child runs rampant. Our first course, I had the squash soup (no animal broth) and it was a bit sweeter than I would think I would like but I LOVED it. Second course, I did eat a little fishy - a seared ahi tuna with avocado and a nice light tangy sauce drizzled atop and arranged as a beautfil butterfly. My entree was an amazing savory tart with goat cheese, that was divine and just the right size. Both of these vegetarian choices were on the menu proper, but the server didnt hesitate to point out the chef would happily pull something else together for me too. The server, Michael, was just wonderful about pointing out what was veg, what could be made veg, and in what order he would recommend we eat it. He also recommended a stellar cheese. We followed the entrees with the cheese course and OH MY GOD folks are not kidding about living in that cart as prime real estate. I could have a whole dinner just off that thing. The cheese guy is a full-on cheesey guru. His recommendations were spot-on and every bite was heaven. Final course was dessert. We had the chocolate souffle and apple bread pudding. I liked the souffle the best, but the bread pudding was very nice. This was followed by a little plate of sweet treats with a birthday candle. And THIS was followed by chocolate mousse with yet another birthday candle. These guys know how to make a gal feel special, and more than a little un-hungry. As I lurched towards the door (yes, two cocktails and more than my share of a great bottle of wine did throw me offstride) Michael handed me a little velvet bag. "A birthday present" he said. Can you guess what it was? A PURSE HOOK. I am thrilled and it is now happily attached to my desk at work. I love this place. If you want to make someone feel special, bring him/her here. All in all an extraordinary night. Sidenote: Why in the world would you mark a fine dining restaurant down a couple of stars simply for being a fine dining restaurant?! That simply makes no sense.

Gary Danko's was perhaps the worst "fine dining" experience I have ever had. To begin with, we are asked to stand for 20 minutes past our 9:30 Wednesday reservation, setting the tone for the rest of the evening. We each ordered 4 courses. The first began with a lackluster salad for my wife, and a fennel bisque with a teaspoon of lobster. The amount of lobster would be no issue, except that it was drowned in two cups of the soup. When I am served my second course, the foie gras stuffed quail, I patiently wait for my wife's course to arrive. After perhaps 5 minutes, a waitstaff person notices and asks me if there is anything wrong. I tell her I am just waiting for my wife's course. She tells me that when ordering a different number of courses for two people, one must arrive out of sync. I immediately inform her that we both ordered four courses, she says nothing and vanishes. A short time later another staff appears to ask my wife if she would like her cheeses course served, explaining that they would have served it to her after her main course. The obvious point there is that the Gary Danko staff somehow thought that it would be appropriate to break apart 4 courses into 6 periods, making us each wait without food for at least 1 period while the other tried to wake up from this bad dream. My quail was actually alright, except that instead of being stuffed with foie gras, of which there was none to be found, it was stuffed with mushrooms lightly surrounded by what appeared to be pÃ¢tÃ©, a cheaper, chunkier, and lower quality liver-food. My third course, which was finally served at around 11:20pm, was the coriander braised bison. The bison consisted of two small fillets flanked by mashed potatoes and the tiniest sliver of blood orange. This would be been excellent had the bison fillets not been as tough as jerky, or the knife presented for cutting it something other than a drawer knife. Three courses of disappointment and two sides of aggravation and I am resigned that Gary Dankos is living off a previously earned reputation, and hasn't the slightest regard for 1) running an orderly restaurant, 2) dining experience, or 3) gustatory senses. I inform the next waitstaff who approaches to let the kitchen know our 4th course will not be needed. I suspect she knew why, as there was no question upon my remark. On my way out, my lone car is waiting on the street at the front of the restaurant. I stand there for a moment as the $11 prepaid valet looks puzzled, then I open the door for my wife. The valet, with mouth agape perhaps psychically trying to tell me that someone has glued his feet in place and given him a lobotomy, stands stupefied behind his podium. I ask him for my keys and push additional money into this pauper-monkey's hand, and apparently it dawns on him that I, practically the last person at the restaurant, am here for my car, which he pulled up moments ago and saw me escort my wife into. After I take my keys and walk the 5 feet to my car, suddenly his feet are freed and he madly dashes to the car to place his fingers on the door I am closing. After we arrive back at our hotel, my wife confesses that she didn't want to mention it earlier, but the parting gift they gave her, a pumpkin muffin, was at least 4 days old, presuming the date on it was a born-on and not a sell-by date. During the course of the evening, we are served by 6 people, none of which have bothered to introduce themselves, with our true waiter virtually unknown until i inquired. It is explained to me that they work as a team to help each other out, but I see it as diversifying the workload so that nobody can be held responsible for the disappointing dining experience. Danko's is an absolute disaster. The waitstaff are disoriented, the kitchen is befuddled, and the valet bewildered. If I could give Gary Danko's a negative rating I would, and I will spend the rest of my days warning everyone who gets within shouting distance to avoid Gary Danko's of San Francisco at all costs.

Right away I loved the ambiance of this place. The golden/orange hues everywhere and bright displays of flower arrangements spread throughout the restaurant give a super sexy vibe when set against the dark walls and low light in the restaurant. Gary Danko makes you feel like you're spending your money in the right place, whether you are or not. The service here matches too, as we were treated like the only guests in the house our entire visit. We did show up just a bit early, as it was our first day in town and we were already experiencing some of the drawbacks of traveling 3 hours backwards. A 9 o'clock dinner reservation is already pretty late, but when your body thinks it's 12 o'clock it really begins to hunger, even after a midday snack stop in Chinatown. While we waited a bit for a table to be prepared we sat at the bar and ordered a half bottle of some fantastic Gigondas to get our palettes going. The bartender here was extremely professional, but in a very likable, chatty way. Once our table was ready the hostess brought what was left of our bottle and our glasses over to us and our waiter came over to welcome us. He was very friendly and helpful throughout the night (he even brought us a signed menu), and it was clear that he handled his duty as a profession and not just a job, one of the nicest things about dining in a city so full of great restaurants. Since Gary Danko follows a typical "make your own tasting menu" format, I'll just list each dish with a brief synopsis of how we felt (because this review is long, check my pictures for full course descriptions): Amuse Bouche #1: shaved pork loin - I loved it. The sweetness of the balsamic was subtle, but very effective at offsetting the pork loin. Amuse Bouche #2: warm blini - Wow, to not only get a second amuse, but for it to be this good, was a very nice surprise. This is the type of bite you could sit at a bar and eat for hours and hours and enjoy it just as much every single time. Course #1 (Nicole): scallops - Texturally the scallops were cooked just a right, a good reminder of why they can either be one of my favorite things to eat or one of the worst. The sauce that accompanied them was equally delicious, but I was a little disappointed to get a bit of grit in both bites I sampled, as I don't expect that kind of error in a restaurant of this quality. Course #1 (me): risotto - One of the best risotto's I've ever had, and even better than some of the epic ones I've made myself at home. Just looking at it you might not be able to tell, but it was loaded with bits of lobster. The harmony of flavors was perfect, as nothing was overpowering, but everything complemented so well. Course #2 (me): frog legs - Probably my biggest disappointment of the night came from this dish, as the list of ingredients sounded sublimely suited to my tastes. The frog legs themselves were slightly overcooked, and the pancetta had almost no flavor, I'm still not sure how they managed that. To make matters worse, the puree was entirely too salty, and completely drowned out anything that could have come from the main part of the dish. Course #2, main (Nicole): duck - As expected the quality of the duck here was top notch, and the seasoning on the skin really added a nice earthy flavor, not to mention the duck hash, which was one of the best tastes of the night. The mashed potatoes were good, but not memorable, and overall even though the flavors were solid with this dish I felt it was just lacking some element. Course #3, main (me): veal - I was definitely not a fan of this dish, and had we been somewhere else I probably would have just ordered something else. The texture of the veal was almost too soft, a quality which is normally expected in veal, but not to this degree. It barely seemed like meat at all. The sweetbreads were too mineraly, with nothing to really offset the flavor; the pistachio was nice but barely noticeable. Dessert: flambÃ©e - We opted to share the tableside dessert (and, they only charged us for one person), which is always hard to resist. It has pretty much all of my favorite items from a dessert ingredient list, and you can taste every single one quite distinctly. This is easily worth the $6 extra. Comped Dessert: lemon tart - The folks here were nice enough to bring us a second dessert, on the house, which I loved almost as much as the first. The lemon flavor in this was fantastic, and really did a great job of making you feel refreshed and clean after a nice long meal. After Dinner Nibbles - This was probably the best selection of the post-meal snacks that we had from any restaurant. Quite a few of these were actually very good, and could easily make a great dessert if done on a larger scale. Breakfast Surprise - The chef does a great little banana bread/cake for the ladies to take home, that stays amazingly moist all night until you're ready to open it the next morning. One of the best take home freebies you'll ever get in a restaurant.

    1664 reviews!! This proves what a legend Gary Danko is. This was one of my first Michelin star experiences in San Francisco and having had the privilege to sample more fine dining experiences, I think one star is the correct level

    The restaurant is aiming for the high class dark wood style of posh establishments. The guests here are definitely dressed for a special occasion.

    Unfortunately, the tables are spaced a little close together so there is a little squeezing past by the waiting staff throughout your meal.

    As for the food, I was still in my infancy of fine dining and was perhaps overly influenced by the opinions of critics in my choice of dishes rather than going with my own palate. I did like the complete freedom to mix and match the dishes on the menu to get your exact choice of meal

    I chose 4 dishes:

    1. Soft Shell Crab with White Polenta, Tomatoes, Corn, Basil and Pancetta
    I love soft shell crab in Chinese restaurants and this version was yummy

    2. Glazed Oysters with Osetra Caviar, Zucchini Pearls and Lettuce Cream
    This is where I should perhaps have ignored the 'signature dish' status of this dish although i do like oysters and caviar. To be honest, it was nice but without any wow factor for me

    3. Seared Filet of Beef with Cumin Potatoes, Swiss Chard, Tomato-Corn Relish and Basil Butter
    Thinking I was in the USA and therefore beef should be eaten, these days, I know I prefer other meat better. The dish was very well cooked but perhaps today I would go for quail or lobster main course

    4. I had a nice cheesecake for dessert

    Gary Danko was a great introduction to the world of fine dining and I'll always be grateful for that but I have other places in San Francisco as my go to restaurants

    Gary Danko's was perhaps the worst "fine dining" experience I have ever had. To begin with, we are asked to stand for 20 minutes past our 9:30 Wednesday reservation, setting the tone for the rest of the evening.

    We each ordered 4 courses. The first began with a lackluster salad for my wife, and a fennel bisque with a teaspoon of lobster. The amount of lobster would be no issue, except that it was drowned in two cups of the soup. When I am served my second course, the foie gras stuffed quail, I patiently wait for my wife's course to arrive. After perhaps 5 minutes, a waitstaff person notices and asks me if there is anything wrong. I tell her I am just waiting for my wife's course. She tells me that when ordering a different number of courses for two people, one must arrive out of sync. I immediately inform her that we both ordered four courses, she says nothing and vanishes. A short time later another staff appears to ask my wife if she would like her cheeses course served, explaining that they would have served it to her after her main course.

    The obvious point there is that the Gary Danko staff somehow thought that it would be appropriate to break apart 4 courses into 6 periods, making us each wait without food for at least 1 period while the other tried to wake up from this bad dream.

    My quail was actually alright, except that instead of being stuffed with foie gras, of which there was none to be found, it was stuffed with mushrooms lightly surrounded by what appeared to be pÃ¢tÃ©, a cheaper, chunkier, and lower quality liver-food.

    My third course, which was finally served at around 11:20pm, was the coriander braised bison. The bison consisted of two small fillets flanked by mashed potatoes and the tiniest sliver of blood orange. This would be been excellent had the bison fillets not been as tough as jerky, or the knife presented for cutting it something other than a drawer knife. Â 

    Three courses of disappointment and two sides of aggravation and I am resigned that Gary Dankos is living off a previously earned reputation, and hasn't the slightest regard for 1) running an orderly restaurant, 2) dining experience, or 3) gustatory senses. I inform the next waitstaff who approaches to let the kitchen know our 4th course will not be needed. I suspect she knew why, as there was no question upon my remark.

    On my way out, my lone car is waiting on the street at the front of the restaurant. I stand there for a moment as the $11 prepaid valet looks puzzled, then I open the door for my wife. The valet, with mouth agape perhaps psychically trying to tell me that someone has glued his feet in place and given him a lobotomy, stands stupefied behind his podium. I ask him for my keys and push additional money into this pauper-monkey's hand, and apparently it dawns on him that I, practically the last person at the restaurant, am here for my car, which he pulled up moments ago and saw me escort my wife into. After I take my keys and walk the 5 feet to my car, suddenly his feet are freed and he madly dashes to the car to place his fingers on the door I am closing.

    After we arrive back at our hotel, my wife confesses that she didn't want to mention it earlier, but the parting gift they gave her, a pumpkin muffin, was at least 4 days old, presuming the date on it was a born-on and not a sell-by date.

    During the course of the evening, we are served by 6 people, none of which have bothered to introduce themselves, with our true waiter virtually unknown until i inquired. It is explained to me that they work as a team to help each other out, but I see it as diversifying the workload so that nobody can be held responsible for the disappointing dining experience.

    Danko's is an absolute disaster. The waitstaff are disoriented, the kitchen is befuddled, and the valet bewildered. If I could give Gary Danko's a negative rating I would, and I will spend the rest of my days warning everyone who gets within shouting distance to avoid Gary Danko's of San Francisco at all costs.

    Right away I loved the ambiance of this place. The golden/orange hues everywhere and bright displays of flower arrangements spread throughout the restaurant give a super sexy vibe when set against the dark walls and low light in the restaurant. Gary Danko makes you feel like you're spending your money in the right place, whether you are or not. The service here matches too, as we were treated like the only guests in the house our entire visit.

    We did show up just a bit early, as it was our first day in town and we were already experiencing some of the drawbacks of traveling 3 hours backwards. A 9 o'clock dinner reservation is already pretty late, but when your body thinks it's 12 o'clock it really begins to hunger, even after a midday snack stop in Chinatown. While we waited a bit for a table to be prepared we sat at the bar and ordered a half bottle of some fantastic Gigondas to get our palettes going. The bartender here was extremely professional, but in a very likable, chatty way.

    Once our table was ready the hostess brought what was left of our bottle and our glasses over to us and our waiter came over to welcome us. He was very friendly and helpful throughout the night (he even brought us a signed menu), and it was clear that he handled his duty as a profession and not just a job, one of the nicest things about dining in a city so full of great restaurants. Since Gary Danko follows a typical "make your own tasting menu" format, I'll just list each dish with a brief synopsis of how we felt (because this review is long, check my pictures for full course descriptions):

    Amuse Bouche #1: shaved pork loin - I loved it. The sweetness of the balsamic was subtle, but very effective at offsetting the pork loin.
    Amuse Bouche #2: warm blini - Wow, to not only get a second amuse, but for it to be this good, was a very nice surprise. This is the type of bite you could sit at a bar and eat for hours and hours and enjoy it just as much every single time.
    Course #1 (Nicole): scallops - Texturally the scallops were cooked just a right, a good reminder of why they can either be one of my favorite things to eat or one of the worst. The sauce that accompanied them was equally delicious, but I was a little disappointed to get a bit of grit in both bites I sampled, as I don't expect that kind of error in a restaurant of this quality.
    Course #1 (me): risotto - One of the best risotto's I've ever had, and even better than some of the epic ones I've made myself at home. Just looking at it you might not be able to tell, but it was loaded with bits of lobster. The harmony of flavors was perfect, as nothing was overpowering, but everything complemented so well.
    Course #2 (me): frog legs - Probably my biggest disappointment of the night came from this dish, as the list of ingredients sounded sublimely suited to my tastes. The frog legs themselves were slightly overcooked, and the pancetta had almost no flavor, I'm still not sure how they managed that. To make matters worse, the puree was entirely too salty, and completely drowned out anything that could have come from the main part of the dish.
    Course #2, main (Nicole): duck - As expected the quality of the duck here was top notch, and the seasoning on the skin really added a nice earthy flavor, not to mention the duck hash, which was one of the best tastes of the night. The mashed potatoes were good, but not memorable, and overall even though the flavors were solid with this dish I felt it was just lacking some element.
    Course #3, main (me): veal - I was definitely not a fan of this dish, and had we been somewhere else I probably would have just ordered something else. The texture of the veal was almost too soft, a quality which is normally expected in veal, but not to this degree. It barely seemed like meat at all. The sweetbreads were too mineraly, with nothing to really offset the flavor; the pistachio was nice but barely noticeable.
    Dessert: flambÃ©e - We opted to share the tableside dessert (and, they only charged us for one person), which is always hard to resist. It has pretty much all of my favorite items from a dessert ingredient list, and you can taste every single one quite distinctly. This is easily worth the $6 extra.
    Comped Dessert: lemon tart - The folks here were nice enough to bring us a second dessert, on the house, which I loved almost as much as the first. The lemon flavor in this was fantastic, and really did a great job of making you feel refreshed and clean after a nice long meal.
    After Dinner Nibbles - This was probably the best selection of the post-meal snacks that we had from any restaurant. Quite a few of these were actually very good, and could easily make a great dessert if done on a larger scale.
    Breakfast Surprise - The chef does a great little banana bread/cake for the ladies to take home, that stays amazingly moist all night until you're ready to open it the next morning. One of the best take home freebies you'll ever get in a restaurant.

    Ok it's rare that a place really impresses me that much and this place did that. Not since Melisse in my resident City of Angels, have I been impressed with service and food.

    I ate here solo - something I enjoy doing once in a while, and only because I was on a business trip. The prices here are right on par for good food. I heard the rumor to go here early and wait for a seat to open at the bar, which I did and it worked out perfectly. Many people try this and few succeed during primetime hours.

    The way the menu is setup is interesting, you can select 2 to 5 courses and you can always add to them later so you aren't necessarily strapped if you get full. EXCELLENT IDEA. I chose a 3 course and I ordered all fish dishes since I love seafood. The first was soup and wow I havent had a lobster bisque that good in a while. They place lobster in a small mound then pour the bisque over it while its steaming hot. Being in SF, thats a nice way to warm up. My second was the lobster risotto - wow did that melt in my mouth, and the 3rd was a scallop dish and WOW... I can't say I have had scallops that good IN A LONG TIME. YES THATS 3 WOWS IN A ROW.

    What I like about the bar, is that the bar tender actually converses with you. I like that rather than me just sitting quiet and eating. He helped me actually choose and he kept my drinks filled. Second he would tell me little bits of info about the restaraunt and how they differ from others. I hope to come here with my gf when we go up to SF again. I know the reservations have to be made way in advance, and the money I spent here was well worth it.

    Come here if you can - it does rival the other big restaraunts in SF.
